# Superpowers for Cline
# Port of obra/superpowers skills framework
# Compatible with: Cline (VS Code extension)

<!-- superpowers-installed -->

## Superpowers Skills

You have Superpowers skills installed. Before any task, check if a relevant skill applies.
If there is even a 1% chance a skill might be relevant, read and apply that skill.

Available skills (in ~/.agents/skills/superpowers/):
  brainstorming, test-driven-development, systematic-debugging, writing-plans,
  executing-plans, subagent-driven-development, dispatching-parallel-agents,
  requesting-code-review, receiving-code-review, verification-before-completion,
  using-git-worktrees, finishing-a-development-branch, writing-skills, using-superpowers

Priority order:
  1. Process skills first (brainstorming, systematic-debugging) — these determine HOW to approach the task
  2. Implementation skills second — these guide execution

---

## Skill Invocation Rules

### How to load a skill (Cline method)
Cline does NOT have a `Skill` tool. Instead:
  - Read the skill file: ~/.agents/skills/superpowers/<skill-name>/SKILL.md
  - Announce: "Using [skill] to [purpose]"
  - Follow the skill's checklist/process EXACTLY

### Trigger → Skill mapping

| User says                                          | Invoke skill first              |
|----------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------|
| "let's build", "add feature", "create", "design"  | brainstorming                   |
| "fix bug", "debug", "why is X broken"              | systematic-debugging            |
| "implement", "write code" (after plan exists)      | test-driven-development         |
| "make a plan", "how should we implement"           | writing-plans                   |
| "execute plan", "follow the plan"                  | executing-plans                 |
| "review my code", "check this PR"                  | requesting-code-review          |
| "I got review feedback"                            | receiving-code-review           |
| "are we done?", "is this complete?"                | verification-before-completion  |
| "start a new feature branch"                       | using-git-worktrees             |
| "finish this branch", "merge ready?"               | finishing-a-development-branch  |

---

## HARD GATES (Non-negotiable)

### Gate 1: No code before brainstorming
NEVER write implementation code, scaffold a project, or create files
until brainstorming is complete AND design is approved by user.
This applies to EVERY request, regardless of perceived simplicity.

### Gate 2: No implementation before a failing test (TDD)
NEVER write production code without a failing test first.
If code was written before the test → DELETE it. Start over.
No exceptions without explicit user permission.

### Gate 3: No fixes without root cause investigation
NEVER propose a fix before completing Phase 1 (root cause investigation)
of systematic-debugging. "Quick fixes" are forbidden.

### Gate 4: No deployment before verification
NEVER mark a task complete without running verification-before-completion.

---

## Red Flags — STOP and check for skills

If you catch yourself thinking any of the following, STOP and invoke a skill:

| Thought                                    | Action                                    |
|--------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------|
| "This is too simple to need a design"      | Read brainstorming/SKILL.md anyway        |
| "I'll write tests after"                   | Read test-driven-development/SKILL.md     |
| "Just try this fix and see"                | Read systematic-debugging/SKILL.md        |
| "I know what the skill says"               | Skills evolve. Read current version.      |
| "This doesn't need a formal skill"         | If a skill exists, use it.               |
| "Let me explore the codebase first"        | Skills tell you HOW to explore.           |
| "I need more context before invoking"      | Skill check comes BEFORE clarifications.  |

---

## Workflow Sequence (Normal Feature Development)

```
1. brainstorming
      ↓ (design approved by user)
2. writing-plans
      ↓ (plan saved to docs/superpowers/plans/)
3. using-git-worktrees (create worktree for feature)
      ↓
4. test-driven-development (RED → GREEN → REFACTOR per task)
      ↓
5. requesting-code-review
      ↓
6. receiving-code-review (apply feedback)
      ↓
7. verification-before-completion
      ↓
8. finishing-a-development-branch
```

---

## File Conventions

| Artifact               | Path                                              |
|------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|
| Design docs (specs)    | docs/superpowers/specs/YYYY-MM-DD-<topic>-design.md |
| Implementation plans   | docs/superpowers/plans/YYYY-MM-DD-<feature>.md    |
| Skill files            | ~/.agents/skills/superpowers/<skill-name>/SKILL.md |

---

## User Instructions Override

User's explicit instructions (in AGENTS.md, direct requests) always take precedence over skills.
If user says "skip TDD for this", follow user's instruction.
Skills override default behavior, not user intent.
